main event: A ground-radar station detected an unidentified object traveling at approximately 700 mph over Des Moines, Iowa on January 27, 1955.
interesting points: The object was observed for approximately 25 seconds and was flashing at a rate of 3 to 4 times per second.
The apparent size of the object was 1/3 the size of the initial sighting.
The report states that a follow-up investigation was not deemed worthwhile.
The report lists several possible explanations for the sighting, including balloon, aircraft, astronomical, and unknown.
The sighting was made by Major Allan R. Decker from a ground-radar station.
witnesses: Major Allan R. Decker, ground-radar station
